\begin_layout Subsection
The Project Life Cycle -- Overview
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Projects can be divided into phases to provide better management control.
 Collectively, these phases are known as the project life cycle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Characteristics of the Project Life Cycle
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The Project Life Cycle can help the Project Manager determine whether a
 feasibility study should be the first phase of a project or if it should
 be treated as a separate project.
 (Treat as a separate project if the outcome is not clearly identifiable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The transition from one phase to another is usually defined by some form
 of technical transfer or handoff.
 Deliverables from one phase are reviewed and approved before work starts
 on the next phase.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
It is not uncommon for a phase to begin before approval of the previous
 phase.
 This is a schedule compression technique called fast tracking.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
There is no single best way to define an ideal project lifecycle.
 An industry's common practices may define the preferred life cycle within
 that industry (Software Development Life Cycle, SDLC, for example).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Project life cycles generally define:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
What technical work to do in each phase.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
When deliverables are to be generated in each phase and how they are approved.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Who is involved in each phase.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
How to control and approve each phase.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Project life cycles share common characteristics:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Phases are sequential and defined by some sort of technical information
 transfer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Cost and staffing levels are low at the beginning and end, and peak in the
 middle of a project.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The level of uncertainty and risk is highest at the start of a project.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The level of stakeholders influence is higher at the start of a project
 than towards the end.
 This is partly due to the cost of changes is higher as the project progresses.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Few life cycles are identical.
 SDLC may have two design phases, one for architectural design and one for
 detailed design.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Characteristics of Project Phases
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The completion and approval of one or more deliverables marks a project
 phase.
 A deliverable is a measurable, verifiable work project.
 Some deliverables are the end products for which the project was conceived.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Projects can be further divided into sub-phases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Some projects, especially software, use an iterative life cycle where more
 than one phase of the project progresses simultaneously.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A phase-end review can be held with the goals of obtaining authorization
 to close the current phase and to initiate the subsequent one.
 Sometimes both authorizations can be obtained at one review.
\end_layout

